training_organizations.name: Wisconsin Child Welfare Professional Development System
training_organizations.description: A statewide training system operated via a collaboration between the Wisconsin Department of Children & Families and the University of Wisconsin system. It includes regional training partnerships that deliver standard curriculum to new CPS workers (in both Milwaukee and county agencies) and advanced training to experienced staff. This system ensures that regardless of county, workers receive up-to-date, evidence-informed training on Wisconsin’s safety decision making model, family engagement strategies, and use of eWiSACWIS (the state’s case management system).

training_organizations.name: Coalition for Children, Youth & Families (Wisconsin)
training_organizations.description: A nonprofit that contracts with the state to support foster care and adoption services statewide:contentReference[oaicite:52]{index=52}. The Coalition (formerly known as the Foster Care and Adoption Resource Center) provides pre-licensing training and information to people interested in fostering or adopting, operates a helpline for foster/adoptive parents, and develops resources and workshops to help retain foster parents. By handling recruitment and support functions, the Coalition helps Wisconsin DCF and counties maintain a strong pool of foster homes and helps families navigate the system.

training_organizations.name: Wellpoint Care Network (formerly SaintA)
training_organizations.description: A nonprofit agency in Milwaukee that has been a key provider in the city’s child welfare system. Under the privatized model in Milwaukee County, SaintA (now Wellpoint) managed a significant portion of foster care case management and support services (similar to a lead agency) for many years:contentReference[oaicite:53]{index=53}. Milwaukee’s child welfare was run by the state but services were contracted out to agencies like SaintA. They recruited foster homes, placed children, and handled ongoing casework for their assigned cases. While the state is transitioning Milwaukee’s management back in-house, Wellpoint still provides treatment foster care and innovative programs (like trauma-informed care training) statewide.

policies.AntiDiscrim_Apply_SomeSpecify: When applying for renewal of a foster home license

policies.AltResp_EligibilityMaltreatment: Only certain types of maltreatment are eligible

policies.AltResp_Eligibility_OtherSpecify: Assignment to a traditional response or alternative response takes into consideration an array of factors (including presence of imminent danger, level of risk, the number of previous reports, the source of the report, and/or presenting case characteristics such as type of alleged maltreatment and age of the alleged victim); Assignment to the traditional or alternative approach can change based on new information that alters safety threats or levels of risk

policies.ExtFosterCare_Criteria_OtherSpec: Have an individualized education program; Compliance with school attendance requirements, school district policies, and truancy laws and ordinances; Youth cannot be missing from out-of-home care placement for more than 2 weeks without contact with the agency
